        "prompt": {
          "stem": "A positive integer is called a squaresum if and only if it can be written as the sum of the squares of two integers. For example, 61 and 9 are both squaresums since $61=5^2+6^2$ and $9=3^2+0^2$.\n\nA prime number is called awkward if and only if it has a remainder of 3 when divided by 4. For example, 23 is awkward since $23=5\\times 4+3$.\n\nA (true) theorem due to Fermat states that:\n\nA positive integer is a squaresum if and only if each of its awkward prime factors occurs to an even power in its prime factorisation.\n\nIt follows that $5\\times 23^2$ is a squaresum, since 23 occurs to the power 2, but $5\\times 23^3$ is not, since 23 occurs to the power 3.\n\nWhich one of the following statements is not true?",
          "options": [
            {
              "label": "A",
              "text": "Every square number is a squaresum."
            },
            {
              "label": "B",
              "text": "If $N$ and $M$ are squaresums, then so is $NM$."
            },
            {
              "label": "C",
              "text": "If $NM$ is a squaresum, then $N$ and $M$ are squaresums."
            },
            {
              "label": "D",
              "text": "If $N$ is not a squaresum, then $kN$ is a squaresum for some number $k$ which is a product of awkward primes."
            }
          ],
